{1000}{}{Why is it that an organism is plagued by mutation? What}
{1001}{}{causes some to be born with the defect we call}
{1002}{}{mutation? What causes the creation of mutants?}
{1003}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1004}{}{Let us first briefly explain what mutations are. As you}
{1005}{}{surely know, the entire "blueprint" of the human body}
{1006}{}{is located in the nucleus of each and every cell. The}
{1007}{}{information about how any given organ should develop is}
{1008}{}{encoded in the chromosomes - long  "crumpled" sections}
{1009}{}{of the double helix of deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA).}
{1010}{}{Humans have 23 pairs of chromosomes. On these}
{1011}{}{chromosomes, in specific places known as loci,}
{1012}{}{stretches of DNA are positioned. They are responsible}
{1013}{}{for the creation of a particular trait or set of}
{1014}{}{traits. We call these stretches genes. It would be best}
{1015}{}{to compare them to the individual pages of a}
{1016}{}{construction manual. Four molecules provide the genetic}
{1017}{}{information; the so-called bases ?adenine, guanine,}
{1018}{}{cytosine and thymine, for simplification referred to by}
{1019}{}{their initial letters. The combination of these four}
{1020}{}{letters of the Alphabet of Life gives rise to all}
{1021}{}{living things around us, including ourselves.}
{1022}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1023}{}{Every time a living cell divides itself, its}
{1024}{}{"blueprint" is copied by means of a rather complex}
{1025}{}{process, which provides for a precise transcription.}
{1026}{}{During this process, one pair of chromosomes may become}
{1027}{}{subject to a phenomenon called mitotic crossing-over.}
{1028}{}{This phenomenon is the reason why it is impossible for}
{1029}{}{two identical individuals to be created ?excessive}
{1030}{}{similitude of the genetic code is always to the}
{1031}{}{disadvantage of a species. When two identical}
{1032}{}{chromosomes cross over and an exchange of two identical}
{1033}{}{loci bearing genes of the same type takes place (we}
{1034}{}{call them different alleles of the same gene),}
{1035}{}{everything is in order. Problems start to occur when}
{1036}{}{chromosomes cross over incorrectly. Then, both}
{1037}{}{chromosomes receive a section they already possess and}
{1038}{}{lose a part of the "blueprint" ?which may lead to}
{1039}{}{fatal consequences, of course. Let us, for a moment,}
{1040}{}{imagine a situation when you have a house built}
{1041}{}{according to a construction plan featuring instructions}
{1042}{}{for two chimneys but none for a roof. Amusing, isnt}
{1043}{}{it? The problem is that here, we are talking about the}
{1044}{}{replication of organic and, yes, even human cells. So}
{1045}{}{if the nucleus of such a newly created cell contains a}
{1046}{}{blueprint with two nose structures but none for legs -}
{1047}{}{I think you get the idea.}
{1048}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1049}{}{Now, this may be shocking to you, but these mistakes}
{1050}{}{are quite common. The process of multiplying genetic}
{1051}{}{information is more complex than any other man-made}
{1052}{}{construction. Millions of structures with the size of}
{1053}{}{just a few molecules participate in it, and even though}
{1054}{}{the entire system of evolution is fine-tuned almost to}
{1055}{}{perfection, mistakes occur quite often. Luckily, there}
{1056}{}{are mechanisms in place to correct these errors, or at}
{1057}{}{least limit their expression. Groups of molecules exist}
{1058}{}{which we could call "handymen", which move along the}
{1059}{}{DNA strand repairing any issues they encounter.}
{1060}{}{Another important fact is that every human being}
{1061}{}{possesses two of each chromosome, whereby each}
{1062}{}{chromosome consists of two identical parts }}
{1063}{}{chromatids. Hence, each body cell contains four copies}
{1064}{}{of a given blueprint, even if in different versions.}
{1065}{}{Should one variant be erroneous, others can replace it.}
{1066}{}{It is as if you lost your construction plans for a}
{1067}{}{shingle roof and decided to build a metal roof instead.}
{1068}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1069}{}{In case this mechanism should fail as well, there still}
{1070}{}{is a last safety backup. I mentioned that these errors}
{1071}{}{in transcription occur quite often. Indeed, it is often}
{1072}{}{and if we consider a single individual, in the course}
{1073}{}{of just one day, several thousand of such errors occur}
{1074}{}{in their body. However, it is important to keep in mind}
{1075}{}{that on average, a human body comprises cells in}
{1076}{}{numbers reaching twenty digits! In this amount, the}
{1077}{}{several hundred transcriptions that result in}
{1078}{}{irreparable errors are easily overlooked. You may be}
{1079}{}{aware of the fact that even though each cell contains a}
{1080}{}{complete blueprint, it partakes in only a certain part}
{1081}{}{of the construction process. This means that if, say, a}
{1082}{}{"foot cell" loses its blueprint for the nose, it does}
{1083}{}{not matter ?it wouldnt use it anyway. The odds of an}
{1084}{}{error affecting the exact section of the blueprint used}
{1085}{}{by a given cell are very low.}
{1086}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1087}{}{However, as with all complex processes, here too we}
{1088}{}{find a large BUT. This issue is represented by human}
{1089}{}{sex cells ?the spermatozoa and the ovum. In their}
{1090}{}{development, which is far more complex than the}
{1091}{}{development of bodily (somatic) cells, they go through}
{1092}{}{a phase in which they possess only a single chromatid}
{1093}{}{of each type of chromosome ?i.e. all the plans, all}
{1094}{}{genetic information are not present in four copies but}
{1095}{}{merely once. The second half of each chromosome is}
{1096}{}{later produced according to this single sample, and the}
{1097}{}{sex cell is thus haploid. As soon as the sperm and the}
{1098}{}{ovum merge, a single cell is created carrying a full,}
{1099}{}{diploid number of chromosomes. Nevertheless, if an}
{1100}{}{error occurs in course of this delicate process and a}
{1101}{}{single chromatid is compromised, the error is carried}
{1102}{}{on. It is copied in the completion of the chromosome}
{1103}{}{and after the merging of sex cells, one half of the}
{1104}{}{genetic code of the embryo is already compromised.}
{1105}{}{Luckily, there still is the second half, the other two}
{1106}{}{sets of blueprints (which are equally identical). It}
{1107}{}{may however happen that the damaged allele, the}
{1108}{}{so-called defective gene, may become dominant and push}
{1109}{}{the original, intact version into submission (The}
{1110}{}{process defining the dominant and recessive versions of}
{1111}{}{a gene is largely governed by chance). In such a case,}
{1112}{}{the defective gene becomes directive for all future}
{1113}{}{copies, for all future cells originating from the}
{1114}{}{embryo. Should this happen, it is very bad, as all the}
{1115}{}{cells of the future body will have the correct}
{1116}{}{blueprint but it will be locked away, unused, and the}
{1117}{}{body will instead build according to the dominant,}
{1118}{}{albeit defective plan. And if cells responsible for}
{1119}{}{building a leg lack an active blueprint to build it,}
{1120}{}{they just wont build it at all.}
{1121}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1122}{}{This is the reason why mutants may come to be. In the}
{1123}{}{period when a human body is made up of just a single}
{1124}{}{pair of haploid cell or even by a single or several}
{1125}{}{hundred diploid cells, the odds of an error occurring}
{1126}{}{are the same as always, but any error will have}
{1127}{}{significant, even fatal effects. Such cases, however,}
{1128}{}{are rather rare. The transcription apparatus is}
{1129}{}{impossibly complex and may break down but under normal}
{1130}{}{circumstances this happens extremely rarely. If,}
{1131}{}{however, the equilibrium of a delicate system is}
{1132}{}{compromised, the probability of a defective gene being}
{1133}{}{created rises manifold. The physical processes that}
{1134}{}{lead to such imbalance and to the emergence of}
{1135}{}{defective genes are called mutation factors; the}
{1136}{}{chemical substances with this effect are then called}
{1137}{}{mutagens. Mutation factors, like for example strong}
{1138}{}{ionizing radiation, X-rays or extreme thermal shocks}
{1139}{}{are not circumstances we encounter on a daily basis, it}
{1140}{}{may however be beneficial to mention something in this}
{1141}{}{respect.}
{1142}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1143}{}{It is a generally known fact that hard radiation does}
{1144}{}{not bring too many benefits to our health, but the}
{1145}{}{reason why that may be is less known. Radiation affects}
{1146}{}{the human body in three ways. After radiation hits the}
{1147}{}{skin, the irradiated surface exhibits a rapid increase}
{1148}{}{in temperature and burns. These wounds resemble burn}
{1149}{}{wounds and are treated in the same way. Further, when}
{1150}{}{high-energy particles and waves penetrate tissues, they}
{1151}{}{cause spot burns and cell damage on a molecular level }}
{1152}{}{they destroy the cytoplasmic membrane, damage}
{1153}{}{secretion pathways, and degrade enzymes. This type of}
{1154}{}{damage usually kills the cell, but should this not be}
{1155}{}{the case, the cell is terminated by the third effect }}
{1156}{}{damage to the delicate nucleic matter. The radiation}
{1157}{}{particles hit molecular chains and knock individual}
{1158}{}{atoms out of them. A short exposition to}
{1159}{}{a concentrated beam of hard radiation is enough to}
{1160}{}{render vital genetic information useless, as it becomes}
{1161}{}{full of gaps. A cell affected in this manner is no}
{1162}{}{longer able to synthesize important substances and soon}
{1163}{}{dies. It may, however, happen that the dose of}
{1164}{}{radiation is not lethal, which means that the damage it}
{1165}{}{causes does not lead to a demise of the cell. It may}
{1166}{}{continue to reproduce and live on but the damage to its}
{1167}{}{nucleus will result in a defect. Dysfunctions of}
{1168}{}{internal cellular processes thus give rise to some}
{1169}{}{somatic mutation.}
{1170}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1171}{}{Mutagens were discovered during the Second World War,}
{1172}{}{in 1943, during research on war gasses. Due to their}
{1173}{}{aggressive composition, these substances cause an}
{1174}{}{irregular crossing-over. They impact cell division and}
{1175}{}{the copying of genetic information, insert defective}
{1176}{}{molecules into new genes, and deprive and deperidinate}
{1177}{}{the DNA string, cracking individual "letters" out of}
{1178}{}{it. Alkylating agents are considered to be}
{1179}{}{super-mutagens. As far as more common substances go,}
{1180}{}{cigarette smoke, some solvents, and benzene are}
{1181}{}{mutagenic.}
{1182}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1183}{}{There is a third mutagenic agent ?viral diseases. When}
{1184}{}{a virus penetrates into a cell, it writes over a part}
{1185}{}{of its code by its own, just as computer viruses do.}
{1186}{}{With time, the virus destroys its host cell and moves}
{1187}{}{on to the next one. But it may happen that a viral}
{1188}{}{infection suddenly subsides. Viruses multiplying inside}
{1189}{}{the cell change and stop harming it, or further}
{1190}{}{replication may even be halted. The cell survives but}
{1191}{}{its genetic code is damaged. Some sections are missing,}
{1192}{}{others are shifted and there may even be completely new}
{1193}{}{sections created by the virus. This might lead to}
{1194}{}{completely unexpected mutations the forms of which}
{1195}{}{depend on the specific type of virus and the section of}
{1196}{}{the DNA string it attacked. Still, even these mutations}
{1197}{}{originating in viral infection are rather rare, and}
{1198}{}{normally not expressed. You really need not worry that}
{1199}{}{the common flu would cause you to turn into some kind}
{1200}{}{of monster.}
{1201}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1202}{}{Recently, there has been speculations concerning the}
{1203}{}{treatment of these mutations. The most diverse}
{1204}{}{procedures have been proposed, all of them reeking of}
{1205}{}{quack medicine. Consider what I just wrote concerning}
{1206}{}{the origin of mutations and you must inadvertently come}
{1207}{}{to the same conclusion. The medication would have to}
{1208}{}{penetrate into all cells, mysteriously find out what is}
{1209}{}{damaged (forget about the fact that damaged as well as}
{1210}{}{healthy sections have the same base content, just}
{1211}{}{ordered differently) and repair it. This is utterly}
{1212}{}{impossible. Not just impossible as far as the current}
{1213}{}{state of science, goes but impossible on principle.}
{1214}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1215}{}{And that is all. I believe I presented a clear and}
{1216}{}{relevantly complex image of the issue of mutation, but}
{1217}{}{you still have to understand that this is just an}
{1218}{}{overview of a topic of infinite complexity, as it}
{1219}{}{treats the very nature of the most amazing and most}
{1220}{}{complex process in the universe ?life.}
{1221}{}{**END-PAR**}
{1222}{}{Prof. George L. Webster, M.D., Ph.D.}
{1223}{}{**END-DISK**}

{2000}{}{Just as we are ready for other dangers that threaten}
{2001}{}{us daily, we must also be ready for the danger of a}
{2002}{}{nuclear attack. We know what to do when there is a fire}
{2003}{}{or when someone is injured, but what do we do when an}
{2004}{}{atomic bomb explodes?}
{2005}{}{Let us hope it never happens - but if it does, we must}
{2006}{}{be ready. The explosion of an atomic bomb is so}
{2007}{}{powerful it can rip up trees, destroy houses, or break}
{2008}{}{all the windows; and it can burn you far more than}
{2009}{}{falling asleep while sunbathing. That is why it is}
{2010}{}{important to know what to do if it happens.}
{2011}{}{It all depends on what kind of an attack it is - with}
{2012}{}{warning or without warning.}
{2013}{}{**END-PAR**}
{2014}{}{Civil Defense is working hard to do all it can to warn}
{2015}{}{us of an atomic bomb before it goes off. When they}
{2016}{}{detect danger approaching, the sound of sirens will}
{2017}{}{warn you, wherever you are. When you hear these sirens,}
{2018}{}{you must head to a vault assigned to you right away.}
{2019}{}{Wherever you are, whatever you are doing, you must}
{2020}{}{stop and immediately go to your vault.}
{2021}{}{It is important to head to the vault that has been}
{2022}{}{assigned to you by the Office of Civil Defense. Only in}
{2023}{}{this way can we ensure a safe number of people will be}
{2024}{}{in each vault. Remember your vault well, because you}
{2025}{}{will not be allowed to enter a vault that is not yours,}
{2026}{}{no matter what happens. Failing to remember your vault}
{2027}{}{puts your life, and the lives of your fellow citizens,}
{2028}{}{in danger.}
{2029}{}{**END-PAR**}
{2030}{}{If you cannot find your vault, it is best to ask the}
{2031}{}{nearest Civil Defense worker and obey his orders. Civil}
{2032}{}{Defense workers know what to do and are doing all they}
{2033}{}{can for our safety - your safety.}
{2034}{}{We are conducting exercises to ensure a quick and easy}
{2035}{}{evacuation of all citizens into vaults in case of}
{2036}{}{danger, so you should already know where to find your}
{2037}{}{vault and what to do. Please, do not underestimate the}
{2038}{}{importance of these exercises - they are done for your}
{2039}{}{own safety. And you never know if this time, God}
{2040}{}{forbid, the threat might be real.}
{2041}{}{**END-PAR**}
{2042}{}{In an extreme case, it is possible that the bombs will}
{2043}{}{explode without any warning. The first thing we would}
{2044}{}{notice would be a bright flash, brighter than the Sun,}
{2045}{}{brighter than anything you have ever seen. If you see}
{2046}{}{it, you must quickly duck and cover, no matter what you}
{2047}{}{are doing; there is no time to wait or look around. It}
{2048}{}{is important to remain in that position until the}
{2049}{}{danger passes. If you can, duck under a table and cover}
{2050}{}{the back of your head, just to be sure. If you are in a}
{2051}{}{room without tables or in a corridor, duck and cover}
{2052}{}{tight against the closest wall. Try to lie down away}
{2053}{}{from windows and doors with glass, because the glass}
{2054}{}{could hurt you if it breaks. If you are on the bus, do}
{2055}{}{not wait: duck into the aisle between the seats, far}
{2056}{}{from windows, so the glass does not cut you.}
{2057}{}{The atomic bomb can fall when you are outside. It does}
{2058}{}{not matter where you are or what you are doing, it is}
{2059}{}{important to duck and cover right away. It is best to}
{2060}{}{duck against the closest wall, but if there is no wall}
{2061}{}{around, duck on the ground and cover your head with}
{2062}{}{clothing or at least your hands. Even a newspaper may}
{2063}{}{protect you from severe burns.}
{2064}{}{**END-PAR**}
{2065}{}{It does not matter if we live in the city or the}
{2066}{}{countryside, we must always be ready for the atomic}
{2067}{}{bomb. Yes, we all need to be ready - and now you are}
{2068}{}{ready, too. You know what to do when an atomic bomb}
{2069}{}{explodes.}
{2070}{}{This holodisk was created by the Civil Defense}
{2071}{}{Administration in cooperation with the Vault-Tec}
{2072}{}{company.}
{2073}{}{**END-DISK**}

