{21000}{}{Colonel Darryl Feustel, PROGEMA, Commanding Officer.}
{21001}{}{Private Journal, for personal use only.}
{21002}{}{**END-PAR**}
{21003}{}{October 1, 2077}
{21004}{}{My last day in command at the PROGEMA facility. Today,}
{21005}{}{we complete the closure of this base - from tomorrow,}
{21006}{}{there won't be a soul left. I hope I don't forget to}
{21007}{}{pack anything. The last few days have been turbulent.}
{21008}{}{Everyone is nervous, working hastily to complete their}
{21009}{}{tasks to the ludicrous deadlines being set for us. The}
{21010}{}{fact that our orders came from the President himself}
{21011}{}{did nothing to help people stay calm, either. I tried}
{21012}{}{finding out more about the reasons for suddenly}
{21013}{}{suspending all activity here, but to no avail. The only}
{21014}{}{thing I do know is we aren't the only ones ordered to}
{21015}{}{terminate their activity like this, with no questions}
{21016}{}{asked. I don't like it. When the Army interferes like}
{21017}{}{this, there is always something big cooking. When they}
{21018}{}{moved that large contingent of military hardware to}
{21019}{}{Alaska back in ?6, the next thing we knew we were at}
{21020}{}{war with China within a week. I don't even want to}
{21021}{}{think about what will happen this time.}
{21022}{}{**END-PAR**}
{21023}{}{I'm sincerely sorry we cannot continue our work. The}
{21024}{}{genetic manipulation project has shown progress and, in}
{21025}{}{my opinion, we are nearing the final breakthrough. Even}
{21026}{}{considering the concerns of some of our scientists -}
{21027}{}{that the definitive specimen may not be controllable -}
{21028}{}{we are definitely getting results. I think some of the}
{21029}{}{scientists allocated to the main project are simply}
{21030}{}{being overcautious. Not that I'll take the storage of}
{21031}{}{our subjects lightly - I will personally see that they}
{21032}{}{are placed safely in stasis. Regardless of any chaos}
{21033}{}{that might erupt here in the hours before closure,}
{21034}{}{subject storage is the one procedure we cannot afford}
{21035}{}{to get wrong. I believe that, in the event of an}
{21036}{}{escape, a subject would have no trouble punching}
{21037}{}{through even the sturdiest of this base's walls.}
{21038}{}{**END-PAR**}
{21039}{}{I'm not sure what is going to happen to the people}
{21040}{}{under my authority. The scientists are murmuring about}
{21041}{}{some large base in New Mexico, a supposed joint}
{21042}{}{undertaking being managed by the Army and Vault-Tec.}
{21043}{}{They hardly know the specifics - it seems like rumor}
{21044}{}{and hearsay to me. Hell, I don't even know exactly}
{21045}{}{where that base is located. The scientists are just}
{21046}{}{plain curious, hoping they might be assigned there, but}
{21047}{}{I know for a fact they're going to be stowed away}
{21048}{}{someplace safe. Maybe even inside the vaults. A handful}
{21049}{}{of the scientists assigned to our secondary project,}
{21050}{}{improving human characteristics, are supposed to begin}
{21051}{}{field-testing their results for the Secret Service.}
{21052}{}{Everything is top secret, under the auspices of the}
{21053}{}{President. They are to report to the Navarro base in}
{21054}{}{California and, from there, transfer to God only knows}
{21055}{}{where. The soldiers will be re-assigned to various}
{21056}{}{other stations. As for me and a few of my people, we'll}
{21057}{}{be reinforcing the base garrison at Mariposa. I'm}
{21058}{}{curious as to what awaits us there.}
{21059}{}{**END-DISK**}

